  "body": "<!---\r\nThanks for creating a Pull Request 💖!\r\n\r\nPlease read the following before submitting:\r\n- PRs that adds new external dependencies might take a while to review.\r\n- Keep your PR as small as possible.\r\n- Limit your PR to one type (docs, feature, refactoring, ci, or bugfix)\r\n\r\n🚨 NOTE: Please open v2 related PRs against the `v2` branch.\r\n-->\r\n\r\nCloses # \r\n\r\n## 📝 Description\r\n\r\nThis PR adds 5 new \"Pro-level\" Marquee compositions to showcase advanced usage and interactivity. These examples demonstrate how to extend the base `Marquee` component for complex UI patterns like parallax effects, scroll-linked velocity, and interactive tickers.\r\n\r\n## ⛳️ Current behavior (updates)\r\n\r\nCurrently, the Marquee examples cover standard functionality:\r\n- AutoFill, Reverse Direction, Vertical Orientation\r\n- Custom Speed, Pause on Interaction\r\n- Programmatic Control, Finite Loops, Edge Gradients\r\n- Basic Multiple Rows\r\n\r\nThere are no examples demonstrating physics-based interactions, staggered parallax depths, or non-standard layouts (diagonal).\r\n\r\n## 🚀 New behavior\r\n\r\nAdded the following 5 new compositions:\r\n\r\n1.  **Parallax / Staggered Marquee**: Three rows moving at different speeds to create a sense of depth.\r\n2.  **Diagonal Marquee**: A rotated, full-width marquee suitable for background \"brutalist\" design patterns.\r\n3.  **Velocity Marquee (Scroll-Linked)**: A physics-based implementation where the marquee speed dynamically reacts to the user's scroll velocity (implemented with Vanilla React for performance, no Framer Motion required).\r\n4.  **Hover-Expand Marquee**: Demonstrates how to handle item scaling and `pauseOnHover` without clipping content (fixed padding logic).\r\n5.  **News Ticker**: A text-based, high-density information layout typical for news or stock feeds.\r\n\r\n## 💣 Is this a breaking change (Yes/No):\r\n\r\nNo\r\n\r\n## 📝 Additional Information\r\n\r\nThe `MarqueeVelocity` component was implemented using `requestAnimationFrame` and `refs` to ensure 60fps performance without introducing heavy animation libraries like Framer Motion.\r\n",
